There are times when I feel really ashamed to be European.
Last year, more than a million people arrived in Europe in need of our help, and our response was, frankly, pathetic.
There are many contradictions,
We deeply mourned the tragic death of the two-year-old Kurdish boy, and since then, more than 200 children have subsequently drowned in the Mediterranean Sea.
We have international treaties that recognize that refugees are a shared responsibility, but we have accepted that small Lebanon hosts more Syrians than all of Europe.
We are sorry that people smugglers exist, but we have made it the only viable route to seek asylum in Europe.
We have a labor shortage, but we have excluded those people who meet our economic and demographic needs from coming to Europe.
We profess our liberal values in opposition to fanatical Islam, but we have oppressive policies that hinder asylum-seeking children, separate children from their families, and seize refugee property.
What do we do?
How did the situation reach this point, that we adopt this inhumane policy to confront this humanitarian crisis?
I don&#39;t think it&#39;s because people don&#39;t care, or at least I don&#39;t want to believe it.
But I think this is because our politicians lack a vision, a vision of how an international refugee system created more than 50 years ago can embrace a changing, globalized world.
So what I want to do is take a step back and ask two fundamental questions, we all need to ask the two questions,
The first question is, why is the current system not working?
Second, what can we do to fix this system?
The modern refugee system was created in the wake of World War II by these men.
Its primary goal is to ensure that when the state fails, or worse, the regime turns against its people, people find a place to go, to live in security and dignity until they can return to their homeland.
It was created specifically for situations like the one we see in Syria today,
Through an international agreement signed by 147 governments, the 1951 Convention relating to the Status of Refugees, the International Commission of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees has specified that states must reciprocate the treatment of people on their territories who are fleeing conflict and persecution.
But today, this system has failed.
In theory, refugees have the right to seek asylum.
But in practice, our immigration policies are based on cutting off the path to safety.
In theory, the refugee has the right to be integrated into society, or to be returned to the country from which he came,
But in reality, their fate remains forgotten indefinitely.
In theory, the refugee issue is a shared global responsibility.
But in practice, geography means that countries close to conflict take in the vast majority of the world&#39;s refugees.
This system is not broken because its rules are wrong.
We have not applied it adequately in this changing world, and this is what we need to reconsider.
So I want to explain to you a little bit about how the current system works.
How does the refugee system actually work?
But not from the top down from an institutional perspective, rather from a refugee perspective.
So imagine a Syrian woman,
And let&#39;s call her princess,
For me, Amira represents many of the people I met in the region.
Amira, representing about 25 percent of the refugees in the world, is a woman with children, and she cannot return to their homes because she came from this city that you see in front of you, which is Homs, a city that was once beautiful and historic and is now in ruins.
So Amira cannot go there.
It also has no hope of resettlement to a third country, because that lottery ticket is only available to less than one percent of the world&#39;s refugees.
Therefore, Amira and her family face an almost impossible choice.
They have three basic options.
The first option is that Amira can take her family to the camp,
In which it is possible to get help, but there are very few expectations for Amira and her family.
The camps are in bleak, barren places, often in the desert.
In the Zaatari camp in Jordan, you can hear the sound of shells at night across the border in Syria.
There is restricted economic activity.
Education is often of poor quality.
Around the world, about 80 percent of refugees living in camps must remain there for at least five years.
It is a miserable life, and perhaps this is the reason, in fact, that only nine percent of Syrians resort to this option.
Alternatively, Amira can go to urban areas to nearby cities, such as Amman or Beirut.
This option was taken by about 75 percent of Syrian refugees.
But there is also a great difficulty,
Refugees in these urban areas often do not have the right to work.
They usually cannot access aid,
So when Amira and her family used their basic savings, they were more likely to face urban poverty.
Therefore, there is a third alternative for them, and this is the reason why our refugee numbers have increased
Where a princess can seek some hope for her family by risking their lives on a dangerous journey to another country, and this is what we are witnessing in Europe today.
Around the world, we are faced with refugees who often have no other choice between the three options of camp, poverty in nearby urban areas, or a dangerous journey.
For refugees, this option is today&#39;s global refugee system.
But I think it&#39;s a wrong choice.
And we can reconsider this choice.
The reason behind reducing these options is that we believe that these are the only options available to refugees, and there are no other options.
Politicians have framed the issue as a zero-sum issue, such that if we benefit from refugees, we will impose costs on citizens.
We tend to collectively assume that refugees are an inevitable cost or burden on society.
But this is not necessary and they can contribute to society,
What I would like to suggest is that we can expand those options so that everyone benefits: host countries and communities, our communities and the refugees themselves.
So I would like to suggest four ways in which we can change the way we think about the refugee issue.
All four of these roads have a common denominator: they are the same roads that bring us to globalization, mobility and markets, and modernize the way we think about the refugee issue.
The first way I like to think about it is the idea of enabling environments, which starts from a fundamental recognition that refugees are human beings like everyone else, but only in exceptional circumstances.
Together with colleagues at Oxford, I embarked on a research project in Uganda on the economic lives of refugees.
We chose Uganda not because it is representative of all host countries.
not like that. Rather, it is exceptional.
Unlike most host countries around the world, what Uganda has done is give refugees economic opportunities,
It gave them the right to work and freedom of movement,
The consequences are extraordinary for both refugees and host communities.
In the capital, Kampala, we found that 21 percent of refugees own businesses that employ other people, and 40 percent of these employees are nationals of the host country.
In other words, refugees create jobs for citizens of the host country.
Even in the camps, we found exceptional examples of thriving and vibrant entrepreneurial companies.
For example, in a settlement called Nakivale, we found examples of Congolese refugees running digital music companies.
We found a Rwandan who runs a business that allows young people to play computer games from recycled TVs and toys,
Unlike the restrictions placed on them elsewhere, refugees are innovating, and the man you see before you is a Congolese called Dimo-Kai.
Daimyo-Kai arrived at this settlement with very little, but he wanted to be a way out.
So he started a local radio station, with a group of friends and colleagues, rented a video camera, and is now a filmmaker.
He made two documentaries with our team, and succeeded in establishing a business from very little.
It&#39;s those kinds of examples that should guide our response to refugees.
Instead of seeing refugees as inevitably dependent on humanitarian assistance, we need to provide them with opportunities that seek human flourishing.
Yes, clothing, blankets, shelter and food are all important in the emergency phase, but we also have to look beyond that.
We need to provide access to connectivity, electricity, education, the right to work, access to capital and banking.
All the approaches we take to access the global economy can and should apply to refugees.
The second idea that I want to talk about is economic zones.
Unfortunately, not all host countries in the world practiced the same methods as I did.
Most host countries do not open their economies to refugees in the same way.
But there are still alternative realistic options we can use.
Last April, I traveled to Jordan with my colleague, accompanied by development economist Paul Collier, and an idea came to mind while we were there with the international community and the government, an idea to provide job opportunities for Syrians by supporting the Jordanian National Development Strategy.
The idea is for an economic zone, through which we can strongly integrate refugees into work alongside the employment of Jordanian host citizens.
Just 15 minutes from Zaatari camp, home to 83,000 refugees, is the current economic zone called the King Hussein bin Talal Development Zone.
The government spent more than a hundred million dollars to connect it to the electricity grid and roads, but it lacks two things: access to work and internal investment.
What if refugees were able to work there instead of being stuck in camps, they would be able to support their families and develop skills through vocational training before they return to Syria?
We realize that Jordan can benefit from this, and its development strategy requires a qualitative leap from a middle-income country to a manufacturing country.
It can benefit refugees, but it can also contribute to the post-conflict reconstruction of Syria by recognizing that we need to embrace refugees as the best resource for ultimately rebuilding Syria.
We published the idea in Foreign Affairs magazine.
King Abdullah picked up this idea,
It was announced in London at the Syria conference two weeks ago, and its implementation will begin next summer.
The third idea that I want to put in your hands is the harmonious preference between countries and refugees in order to reach happy results like the ones you see here in the personal photos that include Angela Merkel and Syrian refugees.
What we rarely do is ask refugees what they want, and where they want to go, but what matters to me is that we can do that and make everyone better off.
Economist Alvin Roth developed the idea of homogeneous markets, in such ways that the order of preference of the parties constitutes ultimate homogeneity.
My colleagues Will Jones and Alex Teitelboim have come up with ways to apply this idea to refugees by asking refugees about their favorite places, but it also allows countries to classify the types of refugees they want to host based on skill criteria or language criteria and allow them to engage.
Now, of course you need to build in stakes like diversity and vulnerability but that&#39;s the way to increase the possibility of inclusion
The idea of integration has been used successfully, for example, to engage students in universities, and to engage kidney donors with patients, and lies behind the algorithms found on dating sites.
So why don&#39;t we implement the idea of giving refugees greater choices?
It can also be used at the national level. As one of the major challenges we face is convincing local communities to accept refugees,
Right now, in my country, for example, we often send engineers to rural areas and farmers to cities, and this makes no sense at all.
Therefore, homogeneity of markets provides a potential means of achieving these preferences together and listening to the needs and demands of the host population and refugees themselves.
The fourth idea I want to put in your hands is humanitarian visas.
Much of the tragedy and chaos we saw in Europe could have been completely avoided.
It starts from the fundamental contradiction in Europe&#39;s asylum policy, which is the following: in order to obtain asylum in Europe, you have to come spontaneously through those perilous journeys that I have described.
But why should such dangerous trips be necessary in the age of budget airlines and modern embassy capabilities?
These are completely unnecessary trips, and last year, they led to the death of more than 3,000 people on Europe’s borders and within European territories.
If refugees were simply allowed to travel directly and seek asylum in Europe, we would avoid that, and there is a way to do that through something called a humanitarian visa, which allows people to obtain a visa at an embassy or consulate of a neighboring country where they simply pay for their journey by ship or flight to Europe.
About 1,000 euros is the cost to smuggle a refugee from Türkiye to the Greek islands.
While it costs 200 euros to travel by economic flight from Bodrum to Frankfurt.
If we allow refugees to do this, it will have huge positives
It will save lives, we will completely cut off the smuggling market, and it will eliminate the chaos that we see on Europe&#39;s front line in areas such as the Greek islands.
It&#39;s politics that prevents us from doing this instead of a rational solution,
This idea was applied,
Brazil has relied on a pioneering method, whereby more than 2,000 Syrians were able to obtain humanitarian visas, and when they entered Brazil, they were given a refugee status.
Every Syrian in this project enjoys refugee status and is recognized as a genuine refugee.
There is another historical precedent as well,
Between 1922 and 1942, these passports were used as travel documents to allow 45,000 Armenians, Chechens and Turks to travel across Europe and obtain refugee status elsewhere in Europe.
The International Office for Refugees won the Nobel Peace Prize in recognition of this workable strategy.
So all the four ideas I presented to you are a way through which we can expand Amira&#39;s options,
They are ways in which we can have great choices for refugees beyond the three impossible basic choices I have explained to you in order to leave others better off.
In conclusion, we really need a new vision, one that expands refugees&#39; options but recognizes that they do not have to be a burden.
There is nothing inevitable about the cost of refugees.
Yes, it is a humanitarian issue and a responsibility, but they are human beings with skills, talents and ambitions, and they have the ability to contribute... if we allow them to.
In the New World, immigration is not going away.
What we saw in Europe will be with us for many years.
People will continue to travel, they will continue to be displaced from their homes, so we need to find a realistic and rational way to manage this... not based on the old logic of humanitarian aid, not based on the logic of philanthropy, but based on building the opportunities that mobility and globalized markets provide. ,
I assure you that we must wake up from our slumber and urge politicians to wake up and face this challenge.
Thank you very much .
