When I moved to Harare in 1985, social justice was the foundation of Zimbabwe&#39;s national health policy.
The new government emerged after a long war for independence and immediately announced a socialist programme: both health care and primary education became essentially free.
There has been a large spread of rural health centers, where approximately 80% of the population can reach these services in less than two hours on foot, which is a huge achievement of its kind.
In 1980, the year of independence, about 25% of children in Zimbabwe were vaccinated.
By 1990, just a decade later, this percentage had reached 80%.
I felt very proud to be part of this transformation, this revolution.
That sense of excitement and friendship was palpable.
Working alongside brilliant Zimbabwean citizens--scientists, doctors, and activists--I felt connected not only to the African independence movement, but also to the public health movement in progress.
But there were huge challenges.
Zimbabwe reported its first case of AIDS in 1985, the year it was introduced.
I cared for a number of people with AIDS in the early 1980s, when I did my medical training at Harlem Hospital, but -- we had no idea what was in store in Africa.
The infection rate went up about 2% during the first days I was there.
This could rise for one in four adults 17 years from the time I left Harare.
By the middle of 1990, I knew of hundreds of people in a very young year who had become infected with HIV.
I saw many colleagues and friends die, my students and hospital patients, die.
In response to these situations, I and my colleagues established a hospital.
We carried out several interventions to explain condom use.
We conducted interventions in education and work settings.
We did research. We provided guidance to female partners of infected men on how to protect themselves.
We worked hard and at the time I thought I was doing my best.
I was providing excellent treatment, as it was.
But I wasn&#39;t talking about structural change.
Former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan spoke about his personal failure that led to the genocide in Rwanda.
In 1994, he was head of the United Nations Peacekeeping Department.
On the 10-year anniversary of the genocide, he said: “I thought I was doing my best, but after the genocide I realized that there were a lot of things I could have done or should have done to sound the alarm and come together to provide support.”
The AIDS epidemic devastated the health of an unprepared society, and today the World Health Organization estimates that nearly 39 million people have died from this disease. I am not the only one who is filled with regret and remorse for not having done more things sooner.
But while I was living in Zimbabwe, I didn&#39;t see myself as an advocate or politician.
I was there to improve my technical skills, my skills related to my epidemiological research
In my mind, my vocation was to care for patients and do research to better understand transmission patterns in populations and, I hoped, slow the spread of the virus.
I was aware that socially marginalized strata of the population were most at risk of contracting AIDS and dying.
On sugarcane plantations, which resemble a feudal system more than any modern institution, 60% of pregnant women are recorded as being infected with HIV.
I have worked to clarify that the injury is not related to moral decay, but rather to the culture of male superiority, forced migrant labor, and colonialism.
As health professionals, our tools were very limited: we called on people to change their individual behaviour, use condoms and limit the number of partners.
Infection rates rose, and when treatment became available in the West, the treatment that remains our most powerful weapon against this virus, the treatment was not available to the public sector in Africa.
I did not mention the unequal access to these life-saving medicines or the underlying economic and political systems that account for infection rates across much of the population.
I justified my silence by reminding myself that I was only a guest in this country. Sounding the alarm could get me fired, preventing me from doing good work, taking care of my patients, and doing the research I so desperately need.
So I didn&#39;t talk about the government&#39;s early position on AIDS.
I didn&#39;t express my concerns loudly enough.
Some doctors and health professionals will think that I haven&#39;t done anything wrong.
Our agreement with our patients, the Hippocratic Oath and its derivatives, centers on the sanctity of the doctor-patient relationship.
I did everything I could for each of my patients.
But I knew that epidemics emerge through the cleavages that exist in our society, which reflect not only biology, but more importantly patterns of marginalization, exclusion, and discrimination related to race, gender, social classes, and others.
